		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>Well, I love the idea of dynamic factions, but I doubt we'll get it here. I'm anxious to see how factions are going to be in EQII because my understanding is that they've put alot into the system. One of my main focuses in compiling my proposed ruleset was to keep special coding that would be required to implement the server to a bare minimum. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I think we'll get another PvP server sooner or later, but who knows what it will be like. Sullon Zek certainly came out of nowhere, and if the ruleset had been held up to any scrutiny by the fan base before it was announced and opened, everyone would have immediately pointed out the vast imbalances of the teams. I tried Sullon Zek for the first few months because I needed something new to keep me interested. It didn't, and I quit the game until Discord was released. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Now I'm waiting for something as interesting as Discord to come out before I resubscribe. Hopefully I'll get into EQII beta and the game will be amazing. Then I wouldn't have to worry about Sony releasing a workable and compelling PvP ruleset for venerable old EQ. But in the meantime I'll&nbsp;hedge my bets and try to help keep the discussion going here.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Aenor the Betrayer</DIV>
<DIV>Grey Companions, Vallon Zek (old school)</DIV>	
		</td></tr>
